azacWYfwD_QDZE4Og].=C2=A0
SkillMagic is going after =E2=80=9Cyoung users,=E2=80=9D the engineering te=
ams within small companies. Jason told me, =E2=80=9CIf a company is already=
 using a competitor, they=E2=80=99re not a good target right now. We want t=
he companies who are doing it all manually.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
This is one of my favorite things about SkillMagic: it=E2=80=99s identified=
 a valuable niche in a massive market full of competitors who are overservi=
ng customers and generating an incredibly low industry-wide NPS.=C2=A0
SkillMagic is in a Huge Market with a Comically Low NPS
Corporate training and L&D is an enormous market in which almost all of the=
 end users are unhappy.=C2=A0
For new markets, as we=E2=80=99ve discussed before, Total Addressable Marke=
t calculations are fairly worthless. For an existing market from which a st=
artup is trying to steal share, it=E2=80=99s more important. SkillMagic is =
trying to steal share from large incumbents with slow onboarding and overbu=
ilt products, so it=E2=80=99s worth looking at how big that market is.=C2=
=A0
To start, SkillMagic is going after SMBs that don=E2=80=99t currently use t=
raining software. A quick bottoms-up analysis:
There are 2 million SMBs with under 200 employees in the US alone,
Assume $1,000/customer/year
That=E2=80=99s a $2 billion opportunity.=C2=A0
As SkillMagic improves its product and wins its niche, it will expand and g=
o after the Learning Management Solutions, which is currently a $9.2 billio=
n market globally. The biggest opportunity, though, comes from the $370 bil=
lion corporate training market. Before COVID, much of this training was don=
e in-person, but remote work will force companies to adopt software solutio=
ns to replace face-to-face training. If just 10% of that market moves onlin=
e, it=E2=80=99s a $37 billion TAM for SkillMagic as it evolves and serves m=
ore roles.=C2=A0
Even better from SkillMagic=E2=80=99s perspective, Corporate L&D in its cur=
rent form is one of the least-loved products out there, with an NPS of -8.=
=C2=A0
When it moves on from targeting just those who don=E2=80=99t use existing s=
olutions, SkillMagic will face an army of slow-moving competitors, like a D=
avid and Goliath battle in which the smaller, nimbler opponent uses its spe=
ed to beat the larger, heavily-favored one.=20
SkillMagic represents the third wave of training software:
2000s. Early, enterprise-focused incumbents came onto the market with poor,=
 mobile-unfriendly UX, subpar analytics, and long sales cycles.=C2=A0
2010s. In the past decade, improved products like Lessonly and Workramp off=
ered customers a better UX and mobile solutions, but still feature enterpri=
se sales cycles, more general products, and long integration periods.
While the space might seem crowded, there are structural shifts afoot that =
make 2020 the perfect year to come to market with a new solution, one that =
is remote-first, built for engineers, and AI-driven.=C2=A0
